If the roots of the quadratic equation $\frac32x^2+11x+c=0$ are $x=\frac{-11\pm\sqrt{7}}{3}$, then what is the value of $c$?
inference:
Comparing the given equation with the standard form 
$$a x^2 +bx +c =0 \text{, we have }$$
$$a = \frac{3}{2}, \quad b=11, \quad \text{ and } \quad c=c.$$

Since the roots of the equation are 
$$x_1 = \frac{-11+\sqrt{121-8c}}{6} \text{ and } x_2=\frac{-11-\sqrt{121-8c}}{6},$$

So, by the Vieta's relation
$$x_1+x_2 = -\frac{b}{a}, \quad \Rightarrow \frac{-11+\sqrt{121-8c}}{6}+\frac{-11-\sqrt{121-8c}}{6} = -\frac{11}{\frac32}$$

$$\Rightarrow \frac{-22}{6}=\dfrac{-22}{3} \quad \Rightarrow 3=-3$$
Therefore, $c$ has no solution.
$$\text{Final Answer: \boxed{No Solution}}.$$
ground_truth: By the quadratic formula, the roots of the equation are $$x=\frac{-(11)\pm\sqrt{(11)^2-4(\frac32)c}}{2(\frac32)},$$which simplifies to $$x=\frac{-11\pm\sqrt{121-6c}}{3}.$$This looks exactly like our target, except that we have to get the $121-6c$ under the square root to equal $7$. So, we solve the equation $121-6c=7$, which yields $c=\boxed{19}$.
